I believe I've come up with a rather succinct definition for life:

A process which decreases its local entropy at the expense of the entropy of its environment.

I mean, it covers pretty much everything you'd consider alive. A crystal might grow, but that's because the crystal is a state of higher entropy (and thus lower energy) than simply remaining in its matrix. But any cellular life? It all ingests low-entropy things like sugars and light and stuff, and excretes high-entropy stuff like poo. But it maintains that barrier between self and not-self, thus decreasing local entropy.
